Confucius says, =E2=80=9CStudy the past if you would define the future.=E2=
=80=9D Churchill adds, =E2=80=9CThe farther backward you can look, the fart=
her forward you are likely to see.=E2=80=9D
So let=E2=80=99s go back to 1878, when, from inside of his Menlo Park, NJ l=
ab, Thomas Edison worked to light up New York City.=C2=A0
At the time, gas lights dominated the city. Coal gas was produced by heatin=
g coal in the absence of air, then piped from central gas works to individu=
al lamps on streets and in homes and offices, where the gas was ignited in =
the burner and the ensuing, flickering flame lit up previously dark or cand=
lelit spaces, protected by glass globes.=C2=A0
Gas lighting was a mini-miracle: humans were no longer bound by the sun=E2=
=80=99s movements. But gas lighting had its issues: open flames were a cons=
tant fire hazard, leaking gas could cause explosions or asphyxiation, incom=
pletely combusted gas produced carbon monoxide, indoor air quality suffered=
, lights flickered, and both the protective globes and the rooms they were =
meant to protect accumulated soot. There had to be a better way!=C2=A0
And there was. Forty-seven years earlier, in 1831, the English scientist Mi=
chael Faraday invented the first electromagnetic generator, the Faraday Dis=
c, which produced electricity from mechanical motion. It was both groundbre=
aking and impractical for commercial use. In 1867, German inventor Werner v=
on Siemens developed the dynamo, a more efficient direct current generator =
capable of producing electricity on a commercial scale.=C2=A0
In the 1870s, Belgian electrical engineer Z=C3=A9nobe Gramme improved on Si=
emens=E2=80=99 design with his Gramme machine, the first direct current (DC=
) generator suitable for industrial applications. And in 1875, according to=
 Carlota Perez, the Age of Steel, Electricity, and Heavy Engineering was bo=
rn. It would be brought to life by Vertical Integrators, including Edison.=
=C2=A0
In 1878, Edison, already a famous inventor, turned his considerable talents=
 towards electric light. In Empires of Light: Edison, Tesla, Westinghouse, =
and the Race to Electrify the World [ https://substack.com/redirect/5bcae12=
0-4874-4d59-8476-ab0d942c5437?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], author Jill Jones describes the need for vertical =
integration to pull this new paradigm into being:=C2=A0
Each component of the new lighting network had to be designed, tested, rede=
signed, and retested. =E2=80=9CEverything is no new that each step is in th=
e dark,=E2=80=9D Edison said. =E2=80=9CI have to make the dynamos, the lamp=
s, the conductors, and attend to a thousand details that the world never he=
ars of.=E2=80=9D The truth was, this was completely new and complex technol=
ogy, and no one really knew how long it would take to make it work or what =
it might ultimately cost.
Edison=E2=80=99s attempts to light up New York highlight both the challenge=
s and the advantages of vertical integration.=C2=A0
Edison himself did not, contrary to popular belief, invent the lightbulb. H=
e and his team did, however, make light bulbs commercially viable. The ligh=
t bulbs they began working with, using platinum or carbonized paper filamen=
ts, lasted only an hour or so before burning out. Over the course of dozens=
 of experiments, they discovered that a cotton fiber filament could last a =
workable fourteen and a half hours, and by the time New York City=E2=80=99s=
 Tammany aldermen visited the lab in December 1879, Edison showed them a ba=
mboo-filament light bulb which =E2=80=9Cshould last six months with normal =
use.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Of course, there was no established supply chain for bamboo-filament light =
bulbs, and =E2=80=9Cthe directors of the Edison Light Company would not go =
into manufacturing. Thus forced to the wall,=E2=80=9D Edison recalled, =E2=
=80=9CI was forced to go into manufacturing myself.=E2=80=9D Explaining fur=
ther, he told one of his investors, =E2=80=9CSince capital is timid, I will=
 raise it and supply it=E2=80=A6 The issue is factories or death!=E2=80=9D =
By the end of 1880, the Menlo Park light bulb factory, controlled and finan=
ced by Edison himself, =E2=80=9Cwas turning out several hundred bulbs daily=
=2E=E2=80=9D As Jones noted, =E2=80=9Cthe nat=
ure of the new and little unders=
tood electrical science and its many unknowns were dictating these first gr=
oping corporate arrangements.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Light bulbs were just one piece of the electric lighting system, which invo=
lved power generation, distribution, wiring, and finally, the illuminated b=
ulb. Each piece of the system had been proven to be technologically feasibl=
e, but it was up to Edison to make the entire system commercially viable.=
=C2=A0=C2=A0
The whole story is one of systems design, of making trade-offs here so some=
thing might work a little better there, like the story of Base Power Compan=
y in Part I [ https://substack.com/redirect/65e857cb-a917-422f-a28a-531cd12=
6e085?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=
 While Edison made many such trade-offs, one passage stands out (emphasis m=
ine):=C2=A0
Always hanging over Edison=E2=80=99s head was the cost of copper, the bigge=
st and most daunting expense for his central station plan. The cost of copp=
er had inspired his invention of the high-resistance light bulb. But even t=
hat huge savings would not be enough if he was to match, let alone undercut=
, the cost of gas lighting. In the summer of 1880, even as the =E2=80=9Csub=
ways=E2=80=9D were being laid out again and again, Edison had one of his pr=
ofound breakthroughs, coming up with a =E2=80=9Cfeeder and main=E2=80=9D sy=
stem of distribution that mimicked =E2=80=93 under the streets =E2=80=93 th=
e new parallel circuits to be used within buildings. This brilliant new app=
roach would cut copper costs to one-eighth the earlier estimates.
When asked why no one else had thought of this simple and elegant solution,=
 Glasgow physicist Sir William Thompson replied, =E2=80=9CThe only answer I=
