=80=9CThese three enterprises,=E2=80=9D Jones writes, =E2=80=9Cwere all org=
anized and financed by Edison or his closest associates.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
In August 1881, Edison bought a building in a grimy neighborhood at 255-57 =
Pearl Street for $65,000, where =E2=80=9Chome-devised and home-made=E2=80=
=9D devices =E2=80=93 =E2=80=9CEdison dynamos =E2=80=93 powered by coal-fir=
ed steam engines =E2=80=93 produced an initial alternating current electric=
ity that was then gathered from the machine by =E2=80=98commutators=E2=80=
=99 and brushes and turned into direct current.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
All the while, complications led to delays, as Edison=E2=80=99s investors, =
the newspapers, and the public became increasingly frustrated. But on Septe=
mber 4, 1882, after =E2=80=9Cfour years of hard work of the most original, =
difficult sort and almost $500,000,=E2=80=9D John Lieb threw the circuit br=
eaker at Pearl Street and 400 incandescent light bulbs =E2=80=9Cglowed soft=
ly to light.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The delays, costs, and grumbling were forgotten in the flip of a switch. Ed=
ison was a hero, and a rich one. In 1889, Edison consolidated his businesse=
s into Edison General Electric Company, and in 1892, the company merged wit=
h Thomson-Houston Electric Company to form General Electric. The combined G=
E had an estimated market cap of $35 million, roughly $1.2 billion in today=
=E2=80=99s dollars.=C2=A0
That, however, was just the beginning of the War of Currents. The next year=
, Westinghouse won a victory for Nikola Tesla=E2=80=99s Alternating Current=
 (AC) electricity over Edison=E2=80=99s DC when he lit up the 1893 Chicago =
World=E2=80=99s Fair. Ultimately, AC, which could travel longer distances, =
won out over DC.=C2=A0
Historians remember Edison as having lost the war. From a technology perspe=
ctive, that=E2=80=99s true. A true Vertical Integrator, however, General El=
ectric adopted the winning AC technology and plugged it into its system. Th=
e company leveraged its brand, size, resources, and diverse product line to=
 invest heavily into AC and used its large customer base to introduce new A=
C products to the market.=C2=A0
