oat, and advantages compound.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
That was certainly the case for General Electric, whose market cap peaked n=
ear $500 billion in 2000, and spent the better part of the mid-90s to the e=
arly 2000s as the most valuable company in the world.=C2=A0
That =E2=80=9Cif=E2=80=9D is the rub, though. It=E2=80=99s the Great Filter=
 that Meter=E2=80=99s Anil Varanasi told me about. If the Vertical Integrat=
or can pull it off.=C2=A0
So today, in the last installment of our Vertical Integrator series (for no=
w), we=E2=80=99ll discuss what it takes to build a successful Vertical Inte=
grator, the advantages they have, and the size of the prize that awaits on =
the other side of the Great Filter.=C2=A0
What it Takes
Inspired by SpaceX, Tesla, Anduril, and, if they=E2=80=99re students of his=
tory, companies like GE, Standard Oil, and Ford, hundreds of startups are n=
ow building physical products, and investors are warming to the idea of fun=
ding them, at least at the early stage.=C2=A0
What will separate the next General Electrics, Standard Oils, and Fords fro=
m the inevitable mass of failures?=C2=A0
The tricky part about answering this question is that there are no playbook=
s or agreed-upon metrics that apply across industries as diverse as energy,=
 defense, transportation, mining, and healthcare. This is not SaaS.=C2=A0
Valuing a SaaS business is a relatively straightforward exercise. The metri=
cs are well-understood and well-trodden.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThis business is generating $75 million in ARR growing at 125% YoY=
 with a NRR of 112% and 83% gross margins.=E2=80=9D Compare that to other c=
ompanies that have performed similarly, map their relative trajectories, ma=
ybe add a smidge here or take away a smidge there based on the founder qual=
ity or market size, apply some reasonable multiple, and come up with a numb=
er.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s all right there for you in the Bessemer Emerging Cloud Index [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/bcc7f376-5a29-43fb-af74-c18d850be5a8?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and in the ma=
ny proprietary datasets built up over the decades venture capitalists and p=
ublic market investors have been investing in SaaS.=C2=A0=C2=A0
There is no Index for Vertical Integrators. That is a good thing. Indices a=
re the enemy of alpha.
If valuing SaaS businesses is now a science, valuing a Vertical Integrator =
is still an art.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s a very different exercise that ultimately comes down to the si=
ze of the prize multiplied by the quality of the plan and the probability t=
hat the team can execute it.=C2=A0
The size of the prize is relatively obvious. The plan can be analyzed, with=
 particular focus on potential unit economics. But probability of execution=
?=C2=A0=C2=A0
On that question, reasonable minds may differ greatly. Many reasonable mind=
s are too skittish to even venture a guess.=C2=A0
This is why I think that early stage Vertical Integrators are some of the m=
ost mispriced assets in the world until they begin to deliver on their prom=
ise.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s like pricing options, but with very little data. Will a compan=
y that can produce electricity more cheaply than anyone in the world be wor=
th at least $100 billion? Of course. Can they actually do it? Ah, that=E2=
=80=99s the question.=C2=A0
If you break it down, there are two pieces of the analysis:=C2=A0
The plan.=C2=A0
The team=E2=80=99s ability to execute against the plan.=C2=A0
The plan is part strategy [ https://substack.com/redirect/0faf01a8-e8ff-443=
d-af4f-e15273158a4c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ], part Techno-Economic Analysis.=C2=A0
On the strategy side, there are questions to answer like: Why now? What is =
the bottleneck preventing incumbents from making their products better, fas=
ter, cheaper? Which technologies will you employ to make your product bette=
r, faster, cheaper? What prevents incumbents from responding? What are the =
string of coherent actions your company will undertake to build a system th=
at delivers a better, cheaper, faster product in a way that others can=E2=
=80=99t mimic? Who will you need to hire to bring the plan to life?=C2=A0
The techno-economic analysis [ https://substack.com/redirect/f6c91a7e-d2b8-=
4998-8bd9-9b74fe8ad4d7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] (TEA) is a combination technical-financial model that uses=
 everything from component costs to efficiency curves to figure out the pot=
ential costs of a system and help make trade-offs.=C2=A0
If Edison had put together a TEA, for example, he would have included the c=
ost of copper, the amount of copper needed at different light bulb resistan=
ce levels, and the amount of copper needed in wiring his distribution netwo=
rk, among other things. Certainly, something like a TEA helped him decide t=
hat copper costs so heavily impacted systems costs that it was worth design=
ing a high-resistance bulb, despite trade-offs including: reduced bulb life=
span, lower electrical efficiency, and increased manufacturing complexity.
Both the strategy and the TEA boil down to this: is it possible to build a =
new system, starting from scratch, that can deliver a product that is bette=
r or cheaper enough than existing products that you can win a competitive m=
arket against better-resourced incumbents?
In traditional startup lore, there=E2=80=99s this idea that you need to bui=
ld a 10x better product to displace the incumbent. With Vertical Integrator=
s, the question is whether you can build a product with 10x better gross ma=
rgins.=C2=A0
If you can, you have options: lower prices to steal the market, charge the =
same price for a significantly better product and capture the margin, inves=
t margin back into R&D to build a much better product. The right answer wil=
l depend on the situation.=C2=A0
Margin gives you room to operate. Unit economics cannot be an afterthought.=
=C2=A0
On paper, credible Vertical Integrators should show significant gross margi=
n improvements over incumbents, which really should be possible. The point =
of technology is to do more with less.=C2=A0
Plus, in large markets worth attacking, incumbents will likely have compete=
d each others=E2=80=99 margins down to the bones in the industry=E2=80=99s =
modularization phase. Remember: they=E2=80=99re not dumb. They=E2=80=99re o=
perating at the lowest cost they can without burning their whole system to =
the ground and starting over.=C2=A0
The Vertical Integrator has nothing to burn; it can simply start from scrat=
ch and choose the right ingredients from the smorgasbord of modern technolo=
gy, assuming it has the capital and people to build everything it needs to =
build.
The margin advantage won=E2=80=99t always look like that chart above. Somet=
imes, the margin will come from being able to charge higher prices for a mu=
ch better product delivered for roughly the same cost. Sometimes, a la Ford=
, the margin will actually be just as thin but your price will be lower, wh=
ich means you=E2=80=99ll be able to do more volume. In any case, there need=
s to be a plan to produce a product in a large market at higher margins tha=
n incumbents can.=C2=A0
All of that is on paper, though. It comes down to the team=E2=80=99s abilit=
y to execute in reality.
The team=E2=80=99s ability to execute against the plan is the harder, and m=
ore important, thing to judge.=C2=A0
From Confucius and Churchill to Tyson. =E2=80=9CEveryone has a plan until t=
hey get punched in the mouth.=E2=80=9D And Robert Burns: =E2=80=9CThe best-=
laid plans of mice and men often go awry.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Here we are roughly 22,000 words into this series on Vertical Integrators a=
nd I=E2=80=99m about to write something incredibly anticlimactic: it all co=
mes down to the founders.=C2=A0
This is a trope in venture capital, and frankly, it sounds cheesy.=C2=A0=C2=
=A0
At first it seems simple, so simple that you want to dismiss it in favor of=
 something more unique, bespoke, or complex. You=E2=80=99re paid to analyze=
 and invest in businesses, so you do market maps and TAM analysis and pick =
apart the strategy and dive deep into the technology, compare it to other t=
echnologies, map the competitive landscape, track traffic metrics, model ou=
t a base case, bull case, and bear case, trade notes with other investors, =
tap your expert network for their insights, and do any number of things tha=
t makes it feel like the investment decision is based on something substant=
ial. You pick apart everything I just wrote about in The Plan, question thi=
s assumption or that. You come up with smart-sounding reasons that This Wil=
l Never Work.=C2=A0
The thing is, though: a truly excellent founder has done all of this, and m=
ore.=C2=A0
They=E2=80=99ve done it to a level of depth and over a period of time that =
you will not be able to match. They=E2=80=99ve done it not to decide whethe=
r to invest 5% of their pool of other peoples=E2=80=99 money, but to determ=
ine how they are going to spend the next decade or more of their lives, whe=
n, as a truly excellent founder, they have a plethora of very good options =
competing for that prime time.=C2=A0
Almost everything else in venture capital follows this circular logic to so=
me extent.=C2=A0
Truly excellent founders are a compression algorithm.=C2=A0
If you judge that a founder is truly excellent =E2=80=93 has the potential =
to be an Edison, Rockefeller, Ford, Jobs, Huang, or Musk, which sounds outl=
andish until you remember that theirs are the magnitude of company we=E2=80=
=99re after =E2=80=93 that tells you almost everything else.=C2=A0
Most importantly, it will tell you whether they=E2=80=99re able to hire the=
 team of people who are the best in the world at the particular thing they =
do that the company needs. Team is the only determinant of ability to execu=
te.=C2=A0
You will not get certainty early in the life of a Vertical Integrator. You =
won=E2=80=99t get early signs of product-market fit. You won=E2=80=99t get =
growth and retention curves. You=E2=80=99ll just get a plan, one that proba=
bly sounds a little crazy, and some people. It=E2=80=99s up to you to decid=
e whether to bet on their ability to execute.=C2=A0
Which raises the obvious question: what makes a truly excellent founder?=C2=
=A0
There is no simple answer. Like porn, you know it when you see it.=C2=A0
Sometimes, all the things that make a founder great are present in one pers=
on, and sometimes, they=E2=80=99re present in a combination of co-founders.=
 You can read the great Tablet profile on Palmer Luckey [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/fddafe19-3dc5-4f5a-b813-334af11281dc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the Isaacson books on Elon Mus=
k [ https://substack.com/redirect/6e743ecc-4025-4d82-8e9f-f5f594c06950?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] or Steve J=
obs [ https://substack.com/redirect/14defd0f-35bb-49d9-8f8e-40db262ceb2c?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the re=
cent Fortune article on Meter=E2=80=99s Varanasi Brothers [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/69be4a8c-385d-48f5-a917-6049c333f2d6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], any of the profiles of the C=
ollison Brothers, or listen to the Founders Podcast [ https://substack.com/=
redirect/b897e1b8-6399-4d02-a818-beb7e84b1a17?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] episodes on history=E2=80=99s great=
est founders and come away with different ideas of what a truly exceptional=
 founder looks like.=C2=A0
As I was writing this, I came across this paragraph in Empires of Light:
Unlike Edison, who launched his every new invention with maximum public bal=
lyhoo, George Westinghouse introduced his lighting revolution very quietly.=
 No press account heralded the tremendous breakthrough of AC, the bursting =
of the DC shackles. The AC revolution began quietly and almost invisibly.=
=C2=A0
Two truly exceptional founders competing in the same industry at the same t=
ime in the same part of the world, and on the surface, their approaches are=
 diametrically opposed. There is no playbook or right answer. That=E2=80=99=
s the beauty.=C2=A0
That said, there are some things that seem to be present in most great foun=
ders:=C2=A0
Ability to attract and pull the best out of world-class people.
Deep curiosity and bottomlessly nuanced knowledge.=C2=A0
Bias towards action and iteration.
Resilience and adaptability.=C2=A0
Storytelling and fundraising.=C2=A0
Tireless work ethic and energy.
Real commitment to a larger mission and desire to solve a big puzzle.=C2=A0
Ability to hold the whole system in their heads, from 30,000 feet to one in=
ch.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s something else about Vertical Integrator founders I=E2=80=
=99ve noticed that is counterintuitive: they often don=E2=80=99t come from =
within the industry they=E2=80=99re trying to reshape.=C2=A0
Most haven=E2=80=99t studied one particular technology in school that they=
=E2=80=99ll apply to the new problem. They=E2=80=99re definitely technical =
=E2=80=93 at least one person on the founding team has to be able to hold t=
he whole system in their heads =E2=80=93 but they=E2=80=99re more generally=
 technical, in a =E2=80=9Cthat guy can figure anything out=E2=80=9D kind of=
 way.=C2=A0
This actually makes a lot of sense. Vertical Integrators need to figure out=
 an entirely new way to do something that=E2=80=99s been done a certain way=
 for years, and they need to do it with whichever technologies and processe=
s work best as part of the entire system. Being wedded, or even biased, to =
one way of doing things or one technology dulls the advantage of starting f=
resh.=C2=A0
There are exceptions to everything I=E2=80=99ve just written, of course. Th=
ere are common traits I=E2=80=99m missing, and the actual effect of the com=
bination of those characteristics in a person is hard to describe.=C2=A0
If I had to sum it up, it=E2=80=99s something like: they make world-class p=
eople want to do their best work for them. That=E2=80=99s a hard thing to c=
apture in words or lists.=C2=A0
All of which is to say: underwriting Vertical Integrators is so difficult b=
ecause to a large extent, it comes down to judging people against the Hercu=
lean tasks they=E2=80=99ve set for themselves based on clues but no certain=
ties.=C2=A0
This is true to an extent for every startup investment. But the challenges =
are compounded with Vertical Integrators for a few reasons:
These are harder, more complex companies to build than typical startups.
The thing the founder is proposing has never been done.
They may require decades-long commitments to come to fruition, with no easy=
 outs along the way.=C2=A0
They require more capital upfront to even have a shot, which means you need=
 to decide before seeing how all of the pieces fit together in practice.=C2=
=A0
There are some early signs. Maybe they=E2=80=99ve hired incredible early ta=
lent. Maybe they have some LOIs. Maybe they=E2=80=99re incredibly responsiv=
e. Maybe they have sterling references. Maybe they=E2=80=99ve pulled off He=
rculean tasks before.=C2=A0
The further along the company gets, the more proof you have that your gut =
=E2=80=93 that this might really be a truly exceptional founder =E2=80=93 m=
ay have been right. The further along the company gets, and the more they=
=E2=80=99re able to accomplish with limited resources, the more obvious it =
becomes that someone people may not have thought was a truly exceptional fo=
under actually is.=C2=A0
At some point, with enough proven, the valuation snaps violently into line =
with the size of the opportunity. It flips from deeply improbable to somewh=
at probable, even obvious. SpaceX and Anduril have more demand for their sh=
ares than they can meet, and enough capital to do what they need to do.=C2=
=A0
The trick is figuring it out before it becomes obvious, when the capital is=
 really needed.=C2=A0
And at the beginning, you have a plan and the people behind it. That=E2=80=
=99s it.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s not a coincidence, then, that the most successful Vertical Int=
egrators to date were founded by Palmer Luckey (and four specifically skill=
ed co-founders) and Elon Musk. Each experienced previous success. Each brou=
ght a nine-figure personal fortune to bear on his new quest. Each assigned =
a delusionally high probability to his own success before the market believ=
ed that what they were trying to do was even possible. Neither needed outsi=
de capital to get going.
In the earliest innings of the Techno-Industrial Revolution [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/38690eea-f472-4b9f-a5be-f2bb4b0d89a7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], that=E2=80=99s what it=E2=
=80=99s taken. As Trae Stephens and Markie Wagner wrote in Choose Good Ques=
ts [ https://substack.com/redirect/15acbd08-48ae-4fe4-9a00-3e79bfd7bca9?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=
=9CThese future-defining problems are hard to recruit for, difficult to rai=
se money for, and nearly impossible to build near-term businesses around, w=
hich is why they are exactly the types of problems we need the most well-re=
sourced players pursuing.=E2=80=9D
Now, though, encouraged by the success of those companies, and often traine=
d within them, there are founders who are not financially well-resourced en=
ough to put the first couple of rounds on their Black Cards. Which means in=
vestors need to figure out which people have what it takes early enough to =
give them the resources they need.=C2=A0
As you may have picked up, there=E2=80=99s no surefire way to do that. It=
=E2=80=99s a bet with long odds. But I think that these bets are worth taki=
ng, because if the team is able to do what it says, vertical integration ha=
s serious advantages.=C2=A0
The Advantages to Vertical Integration
The world faces a number of very big challenges. It always faces a number o=
f very big challenges. We need food, energy, shelter, communication, transp=
ortation, healthcare, and materials with which to build new things.=C2=A0
Humans are constantly trying to figure out new and better ways to meet thos=
e needs. One generation=E2=80=99s solutions work for a time, until they are=
 outgrown or atrophy. Then entirely new solutions to very old challenges ar=
e needed.=C2=A0
This is a never-ending game: the population grows and each person=E2=80=99s=
 desires grow. More than eight billion people demand comforts not even one =
king could attain two centuries ago. Meanwhile, the companies built to serv=
e those demands under one Techno-Economic Paradigm, struggling just to figh=
t off entropy, cannot serve them in the next.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s up to entirely new companies to create entirely new solutions =
to those ever-present challenges.=C2=A0
In the first three parts of this series (Part I [ https://substack.com/redi=
rect/cabbe5f6-a560-4574-b74b-d48421812a44?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA=
_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Part II [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/65e857cb-a917-422f-a28a-531cd126e085?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and Part III [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/b3473aad-c535-40ae-8c3b-4e6de4d760f3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]), we=E2=80=99ve discussed that, after a =
half-century of solving low-hanging problems with software, the biggest cha=
llenges today require physical solutions. Software alone won=E2=80=99t solv=
e them =E2=80=93 either directly or by patching up leaky incumbents. That m=
uch is becoming obvious. Less clearly, selling components to incumbents won=
=E2=80=99t solve them, either, even if they are atoms-based and therefore i=
n vogue.=C2=A0
In Full-Stack Deep Tech [ https://substack.com/redirect/c9110324-f21a-41e2-=
acf5-c057c96deb32?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ], Cantos=E2=80=99 Ian Rountree explained why these businesses do=
n=E2=80=99t work:=C2=A0
And yet we see so many deep tech startups that aim to sell equipment, compo=
nents, or services into slow-moving, often thin-margin industries. I don=E2=
=80=99t blame them. It=E2=80=99s a less intimidating, apparently more capit=
al-efficient path to market. For these reasons I=E2=80=99ve backed a number=
 of these endeavors over the years=E2=80=A6 but it=E2=80=99s almost always =
been a mistake. You raise your Seed round and sometimes a Series A on a pil=
ot, LOIs, purchase order, or from strategic investment from a major incumbe=
nt. But then they never move as quickly as you and your investors need; the=
y drag out the pilot, move the goalposts, or management changes and you=E2=
=80=99re forgotten altogether.
In order to solve the challenges facing humanity today, for now, we need ve=
rtically integrated companies that aim to build entirely new systems and co=
mpete head-on with incumbents.=C2=A0
We are entering what Carlota Perez would call a new Techno-Economic Paradig=
m [ https://substack.com/redirect/65e857cb-a917-422f-a28a-531cd126e085?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], one defin=
ed by the combination of bits and atoms, and new Techno-Economic Paradigms =
both demand and reward Vertical Integrators.=C2=A0
While vertically integrating in an effort to topple centuries-old incumbent=
s seems insane, it=E2=80=99s the only way to really get the job done and pu=
ll humanity forward.=C2=A0
Vertical integration allows for tighter feedback loops. Hadrian has softwar=
e engineers working next to machinists in order to build better software an=
d automate what can be automated. Radiant built a digital twin of its react=
or to run simulations as it gets data from its test reactor. Earth AI drill=
s its own targets to quickly learn which are promising. Primer can adjust i=
ts curriculum to individual students instead of waiting for Boards of Educa=
tion to agree on new curricula for all students. In each case, the companie=
s get feedback, and can iterate towards better systems, much faster than th=
ey could if they outsourced core capabilities or had to wait to sell their =
product to slow-moving incumbents.=C2=A0
Vertical integration allows for trade-offs at the system level as opposed t=
o the product level. Base Power Company makes decisions that you might not =
make if you were just manufacturing battery packs to sell to customers in o=
rder to make packs easier to install. They call the whole process the Deplo=
yment Factory. That gives them more control of the overall system than they=
 would have buying packs from third-parties or selling them to customers.=
=C2=A0
Vertical Integrators ride exogenous technology curves to build products tha=
t naturally get better over time. Base will take advantage of improvements =
in cell chemistries, and in the increased demand for their product from inc=
reased renewable (variable) power generation and electrification. Fuse [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/1e94931c-e454-4f8d-8a3d-8855f6b451a0?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] benefits from th=
e improved performance of the capacitors it relies on for its pulsed-power =
generators.=C2=A0
Relatedly, they don=E2=80=99t face existential risk from a single new techn=
ology. Their value is in the system, not in any one of the pieces. A compet=
itor with a better technology would have to build a vertically integrated s=
ystem around that technology in order to compete. Sometimes, the Vertical I=
ntegrator might simply be able to plug in that new technology to improve th=
e performance of the whole system. Think of the distinction Sam Altman made=
 on 20VC [ https://substack.com/redirect/b761fbaa-a679-401e-b8b0-99ed5596f3=
60?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] abo=
ut building products with AI that new models might crush versus those that =
benefit from improved models.=C2=A0
Vertical Integrators can control their own supply chains and bring their ow=
n core technologies down those curves. Radiant plans to manufacture nuclear=
 reactors in factories, hopefully bringing reactors onto the learning curve=
s typically experienced by mass manufactured products. Fuse, while benefiti=
ng to date from improved capacitor performance, can manufacture pulsed-powe=
r generators both for itself and to sell to other fusion companies in order=
 to produce more, bring down costs, and improve performance en route to com=
mercial fusion. Like Amazon with AWS, these companies can be their own firs=
t and best customer.=C2=A0
Vertical Integrators don=E2=80=99t have to do anything unproven to build be=
tter products than exist. Deep tech companies often require doing something=
 that=E2=80=99s never been done before, before running out of money, and th=
en scaling that thing in order to unlock value. Vertical Integrators need t=
o combine a number of very hard things that are at least each possible. The=
y take on engineering and system risk, but not scientific or technical risk=
=2E=C2=A0
Vertically integrating means better margins, if it works, at scale. A tight=
ly-managed manufacturing process can bring down costs. Better, there are si=
mply fewer external parties to split margin with the more you vertically in=
tegrate, and you are in more control of your margins than if you try to sel=
l into legacy industrials who have more power in the relationship than you =
do. Study Porter=E2=80=99s Five Forces.=C2=A0
Vertical Integration allows companies to deliver products that they couldn=
=E2=80=99t if they didn=E2=80=99t control the full-stack. SpaceX was able t=
o launch the largest telecommunications network in the world by owning reli=
able launch capabilities. Meter launched Command [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/abed6e0d-02c6-4625-9265-d67bc7d57c96?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], a product that allows customers to un=
derstand and take action on their networks using natural language, because =
it controls everything from hardware to the data pipeline.=C2=A0
Finally, vertically integrating means competing for the biggest prizes. It =
means tapping into the multi-trillion dollar pools of revenue available to =
the companies that solve whole problems for their customers, and =E2=80=9Cs=
triking not at the margins of the profits and the outputs of the existing f=
irms but at their foundations and their very lives.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Simply put, while the struggle is real, the opportunity is commensurately l=
arge. Those few that succeed will have the chance to build some of the larg=
est and most impactful companies in history.=C2=A0
The Size of the Prize
One of the things that first drew my attention to Vertical Integrators was =
that a lot of founders who seemed to be smart and (the right amount of) san=
e were trying to build them. That=E2=80=99s usually a good early signal tha=
t something is brewing. What the smartest people will do on the weekend is =
what everyone else will be doing in ten years [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/c15e583a-18d3-4a4b-95c5-b8cc5d878972?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], but for a category you can=E2=80=99t rea=
lly do on the weekend.=C2=A0
The thing that really grabbed me from there, before I had a framework or ev=
en knew I was looking at different instances of the same phenomenon, was th=
e sheer size of the opportunities. I remember my first conversation with Ha=
drian=E2=80=99s Chris Power, as he explained what he was trying to do, sayi=
ng something like, =E2=80=9CIf you pull this off, this is a $100 billion co=
mpany.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s a lot of execution between here and there, but my convictio=
n that there will be many $100 billion startups created by delivering bette=
r products than incumbents at lower costs and higher margins has only grown=
 since.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s one of the most tantalizing things about Vertical Integrator=
s: there is a clear path to tremendously large outcomes. Not easy, but clea=
r.=C2=A0
With the previous generation=E2=80=99s winners, you had to bet that the mar=
ket would change in some dramatic way to see how these startups might becom=
e giants.=C2=A0
Google was one of many search engines indexing a relatively tiny universe o=
f websites, with no business model to speak of. Amazon sold books! On the i=
nternet! When Barnes & Noble existed! Facebook was a place for college kids=
 to look at pictures of each other, with a lot of eyeballs and no ads. Even=
 Uber and Airbnb, with their modern approaches to established industries, r=
equired investors to expand their thinking about the market in which those =
companies were operating.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Their early execution and growth were hard to argue with, but grasping the =
size of the opportunity if that growth continued, when the numbers said tha=
t growth couldn=E2=80=99t continue given the market sizes of the day, might=
 have required a heavy dose of hallucinogens.=C2=A0
Vertical Integrators find themselves in almost exactly the opposite situati=
on.=C2=A0
The size of the opportunity is relatively clear in the revenue numbers of t=
he incumbents they seek to replace, but their ability to execute is uncerta=
in and early growth is practically non-existent. In the place of smooth gro=
wth curves, there are discrete gates, often years in the future, that they =
need to pass through to prove value.=C2=A0
That means that none of the old playbooks, meticulously compiled over decad=
es of watching companies like Google, Amazon, Facebook, Uber, Airbnb, or hu=
ndreds of SaaS companies, work for building or investing in Vertical Integr=
ators.=C2=A0
Which is why I think they=E2=80=99re the most mispriced assets in venture c=
apital. Again, it comes down to the size of the prize multiplied by the pla=
n and the probability you assign to the team=E2=80=99s ability to execute i=
t.=C2=A0
Throughout this series, I=E2=80=99ve tried to make the case that most peopl=
e are underestimating the probability, at least in aggregate.=C2=A0
In Part I [ https://substack.com/redirect/cabbe5f6-a560-4574-b74b-d48421812=
a44?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], I=
 argued that Vertical Integrators were distinct from either Aggregators or =
Deep Tech companies, that the problems left over from the Aggregator era re=
quire vertically integrated solutions, and that Vertical Integrators=E2=80=
=99 business models =E2=80=9Cshould look more like the business models that=
 won the Second Industrial Revolution.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
In Part II [ https://substack.com/redirect/65e857cb-a917-422f-a28a-531cd126=
e085?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =
I showed that there are pretty compelling signs that we=E2=80=99re entering=
 a new Techno-Economic Paradigm. Historically, these new beginnings have bo=
th required and rewarded Vertical Integrators, like Edison, who can build n=
ew systems with new technologies to deliver the new products that the marke=
t needs.=C2=A0
In Part III [ https://substack.com/redirect/b3473aad-c535-40ae-8c3b-4e6de4d=
760f3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ],=
 I discussed that while all of that sounds great in theory, actually doing =
it is fraught with very real challenges. Many startups that have tried to v=
ertically integrate too early, or in not quite the right way, have died exp=
ensive deaths.=C2=A0
Today, we talked about what it takes to overcome those challenges: sound pl=
ans backed by strong potential unit economics and the rare founders and tea=
ms who can execute against those plans. We also talked about some of the ad=
vantages available to the small few who can pull it off.=C2=A0
The biggest advantage may be this: because it=E2=80=99s so difficult, and b=
ecause the advantages you accumulate by doing a million hard things well fo=
rm barriers, there will be very little serious competition awaiting on the =
other side of the Great Filter.=C2=A0
Of course, incumbents will be there, and they will try to compete. But if t=
hese companies are able to execute on the plans that show 10x better margin=
s than incumbents (i.e. 50% vs. 5%) in ways that would force incumbents to =
abandon what got them here just to try to turn their very large and unwield=
y ships in time, while public market investors scream at them for burning c=
ash, my money is on the Vertical Integrator.=C2=A0
Among startups, I expect we=E2=80=99ll see much less competition. The compa=
nies that show an early ability to execute against a big and credible enoug=
h vision will attract the top talent and the limited pool of investors will=
ing to back such hard-to-underwrite companies, sucking the air out of the r=
oom for would-be challengers.=C2=A0
There may be a mini-funding bubble once a few more of these companies break=
 out and investors come to adjust their probabilities, but the limiting fac=
tors will remain talent and the ability to design, build, and balance the c=
omplex integrated system necessary to compete.=C2=A0
Plus, the first startups that are able to deliver will build trusted brands=
 that partners can count on. All else equal, would you trust your valuable =
payload to a launch company not named SpaceX? All else equal, would you put=
 the second best advanced nuclear reactor in your community?=C2=A0
All of this points to the idea that there will be some truly massive vertic=
ally integrated companies built in the next couple of decades. I would not =
be surprised to see at least a dozen companies founded in the 2020s and 203=
0s reach trillion-dollar market caps by 2040 or 2050. Tech has barely start=
ed to touch the very big sectors of the economy.=C2=A0
There are too many trillion-dollar industries that are struggling to keep u=
p or improve, and too many truly exceptional founders with too many powerfu=
l new technologies at their disposal, for the world not to look much differ=
ent in a couple of decades than it does today.=C2=A0
Energy, manufacturing, defense, transportation, mining, construction, agric=
ulture, and healthcare =E2=80=93 each a multi-trillion dollar industry =E2=
=80=93 is ripe for creative destruction. If anything, better products at lo=
wer prices will only expand those markets, and higher margins will make the=
 companies that win them more valuable than the incumbents they replace.
Even labor, largely unaddressable by technology to date, is ripe for Vertic=
al Integration. At some point, robots will perform much of the backbreaking=
 physical labor done by humans today, and it seems clear that AI will take =
on a good deal of today=E2=80=99s knowledge work.=C2=A0
While we=E2=80=99ve explored vertical integration in the context of compani=
es building physical products, I suspect that vertical integration =E2=80=
=93 internalizing whatever necessary to fully do the job for customers =E2=
=80=93 will touch all industries.=C2=A0
If you look at what Ramp [ https://substack.com/redirect/f5358133-479a-41fd=
-9839-32a710261c38?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ] is building towards, for example, it=E2=80=99s agents that do =
much of the work that finance teams do today. There will be agents for each=
 department - sales, engineering, design, etc=E2=80=A6 =E2=80=93 each a pro=
duct that does a job better, faster, cheaper. Similarly, I suspect we=E2=80=
=99ll see whole services firms =E2=80=93 accounting, legal, consulting =E2=
=80=93 vertically integrated around AI-native capabilities that have signif=
icant cost advantages over incumbents, and whose advantages grow with scale=
 and data. YC=E2=80=99s Jared Friedman called them =E2=80=9Cvertical agents=
=E2=80=9D in a tweet last night [ https://substack.com/redirect/fe278907-f7=
75-4cc7-9ac9-0aa9c3deeb55?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
If you think about what an agent or AI-first firm might be able to do in fi=
ve or ten years, the companies that build the best ones look a lot like Ver=
tical Integrators:=C2=A0
Integrate multiple cutting-edge-but-proven technologies.
Develop significant in-house capabilities across their stack.
Modularize commoditized components while controlling overall system integra=
tion.
Compete directly with incumbents.
Offer products that are better, faster, or cheaper (often all three).
In short, in a new Techno-Economic Paradigm, every industry will be reshape=
d, and they will be reshaped by Vertical Integrators. Right now, at the end=
 of an old TEP and the beginning of a new one, things are uncertain, even s=
cary.=C2=A0
But history says that humanity will experience wonders that even I, as opti=
mistic as I am, can=E2=80=99t imagine. The period between the dawn of Perez=
=E2=80=99s first TEP =E2=80=93 the Industrial Revolution =E2=80=93 through =
the beginning of the last =E2=80=93 the Information Age =E2=80=93 saw the i=
nvention of miracles that would have made an early 18th century person=E2=
=80=99s head explode.=C2=A0
If I=E2=80=99m right, after half-a century of incredible progress in the wo=
rld of bits, the combination of bits and atoms, brought about by Vertical I=
ntegrators, will blow our minds, too.=C2=A0
We will see cheap, abundant energy, cures for our most deadly diseases, sup=
ersonic flight, robots that do our chores, cars that drive us, homes people=
 can afford, adventures in space, and much more besides.=C2=A0
But are these companies that create these miracles venture backable? I thin=
k they=E2=80=99re among the only companies that are.=C2=A0
That may be a controversial thing to say, when new AI-powered SaaS companie=
s are hitting $10s of millions of revenue in the first year while Vertical =
Integrators take years and $10s of millions of dollars to get to first reve=
nue, but it=E2=80=99s important to remember that it takes 7-10 years, at a =
minimum, to get to IPO.=C2=A0
One question you need to ask is: with everything changing as fast as it is,=
 do I see this company surviving and continuing to grow a decade from now?=
=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s a hard question to answer for companies that catch fire earl=
y and attract waves of competitors with the tools to build products in days=
 that would have taken months.=C2=A0
Vertical Integrators are the opposite bet. They=E2=80=99re more uncertain a=
nd capital intensive early, but those things flip with time. As Ian Rountre=
e wrote in Full-Stack Deep Tech [ https://substack.com/redirect/c9110324-f2=
1a-41e2-acf5-c057c96deb32?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Though full-stack startups may initially be more capital intensive we belie=
ve that they are ultimately more capital efficient.
Once Vertical Integrators prove that they can do what they say they=E2=80=
=99re going to do, they unlock access to non-dilutive financing and practic=
ally bottomless markets with very little competition. It may take 7-10 year=
s to start generating meaningful revenue, but it=E2=80=99s much easier to i=
magine these companies being around in a century once they do.=C2=A0
Their longevity means clearer paths to big outcomes, and the dependability =
to become platforms themselves.=C2=A0
Just as Edison and Westinghouse laid the wiring for a surge of businesses n=
ewly possible and improved by reliable electricity, the Vertical Integrator=
s that bring this new Techno-Economic Paradigm into being will become a pla=
tform for entirely new businesses.=C2=A0
This is already happening with SpaceX =E2=80=93 a big part of the =E2=80=9C=
why now?=E2=80=9D for every space startup =E2=80=93 and it=E2=80=99s not ha=
rd to imagine that there will be thousands of businesses made possible by c=
heaper energy, faster construction, faster travel, longer, healthier lives,=
 better food, and automated manufacturing and labor, even if it=E2=80=99s h=
ard to imagine exactly what those businesses will look like.=C2=A0
These businesses =E2=80=93 the Vertical Integrators and the new businesses =
they make possible =E2=80=93 will benefit humanity as much or more than the=
 Industrial Revolution and the Second Industrial did. With better tools [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/e90d8fa1-1b35-4c5c-9dfe-263766a630ad?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and faster pro=
gress, we can solve ever-harder challenges.=C2=A0
But if history is a guide, none will capture more value than the intrepid V=
ertical Integrators that figure out how these new tools fit together and se=
t the stage for the half-century to come. =C2=A0
That doesn=E2=80=99t mean it will be easy. In fact, it will be very, very h=
ard. There will be billion-dollar flameouts and promising technologies that=
 get punched in the mouth by manufacturing.=C2=A0
But some will make it through, and they will be very valuable, both financi=
ally and societally.=C2=A0 Stay tuned for the Deep Dives to hear the storie=
s of the ones to which I assign the highest probabilities in real-time.=C2=
=A0
Ultimately, the companies that bring these miracles into existence will be =
rightly rewarded for doing so, for they will have defined and improved the =
future. It=E2=80=99s time to vertically integrate.=C2=A0
Thanks to Claude for editing.
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Friday=
 with a Weekly Dose.
Thanks for reading,
Packy

