, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In the =
1870s, Belgian electrical engineer Z&#233;nobe Gramme improved on Siemens&#=
8217; design with his Gramme machine, the first direct current (DC) generat=
or suitable for industrial applications. And in 1875, according to Carlota =
Perez, the Age of Steel, Electricity, and Heavy Engineering was born. It wo=
uld be brought to life by Vertical Integrators, including Edison.&#160;</p>=
<p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; mar=
gin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In 1878, Edison, already a famous inventor, turned =
his considerable talents towards electric light. In </span><em><a href=3D"h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/5bcae120-4874-4d59-8476-ab0d942c5437?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"col=
or: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">Empires of Light: Edison,=
 Tesla, Westinghouse, and the Race to Electrify the World</a></em><span>, a=
uthor Jill Jones describes the need for vertical integration to pull this n=
ew paradigm into being:&#160;</span></p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4=
px solid #0c2427; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 5=
5, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left=
: 20px;"><em><span>Each component of the new lighting network had to be des=
igned, tested, redesigned, and retested. &#8220;Everything is no new that e=
ach step is in the dark,&#8221; Edison said. &#8220;I have to make the dyna=
mos, the lamps, the conductors, and attend to a thousand details that the w=
orld never hears of.&#8221; </span><strong>The truth was, this was complete=
ly new and complex technology, and no one really knew how long it would tak=
e to make it work or what it might ultimately cost.</strong></em></p></bloc=
kquote><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Edison&#8217;s attempts to light up New York highl=
ight both the challenges and the advantages of vertical integration.&#160;<=
/p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; =
margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Edison himself did not, contrary to popular beli=
ef, invent the lightbulb. He and his team did, however, make light bulbs </=
span><strong>commercially viable</strong><span>. The light bulbs they began=
 working with, using platinum or carbonized paper filaments, lasted only an=
 hour or so before burning out. Over the course of dozens of experiments, t=
hey discovered that a cotton fiber filament could last a workable fourteen =
and a half hours, and by the time New York City&#8217;s Tammany aldermen vi=
sited the lab in December 1879, Edison showed them a bamboo-filament light =
bulb which &#8220;should last six months with normal use.&#8221;&#160;</spa=
n></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Of course, there was no established supply ch=
ain for bamboo-filament light bulbs, and &#8220;the directors of the Edison=
 Light Company would not go into manufacturing. Thus forced to the wall,&#8=
221; Edison recalled, &#8220;I was forced to go into manufacturing myself.&=
#8221; Explaining further, he told one of his investors, &#8220;Since capit=
al is timid, I will raise it and supply it&#8230; </span><strong>The issue =
is factories or death!</strong><span>&#8221; By the end of 1880, the Menlo =
Park light bulb factory, controlled and financed by Edison himself, &#8220;=
was turning out several hundred bulbs daily.&#8221; As Jones noted, &#8220;=
the nature of the new and little understood electrical science and its many=
 unknowns were dictating these first groping corporate arrangements.&#8221;=
&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-=
height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Light bulbs were just one piece of the e=
lectric lighting system, which involved power generation, distribution, wir=
ing, and finally, the illuminated bulb. Each piece of the system had been p=
roven to be technologically feasible, but it was up to Edison to make the e=
ntire system commercially viable.&#160;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54,=
 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Th=
e whole story is one of systems design, of making trade-offs here so someth=
ing might work a little better there, like the story of Base Power Company =
in </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/65e857cb-a917-422f-a28a-=
531cd126e085?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">Par=
t I</a><span>. While Edison made many such trade-offs, one passage stands o=
ut (emphasis mine):&#160;</span></p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px s=
olid #0c2427; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 5=
5); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20=
px;"><em><span>Always hanging over Edison&#8217;s head was the cost of copp=
er, the biggest and most daunting expense for his central station plan. </s=
pan><strong>The cost of copper had inspired his invention of the high-resis=
tance light bulb</strong><span>. But even that huge savings would not be en=
ough if he was to </span><strong>match, let alone undercut, the cost of gas=
 lighting.</strong><span> In the summer of 1880, even as the &#8220;subways=
&#8221; were being laid out again and again, Edison had one of his profound=
 breakthroughs, coming up with a &#8220;feeder and main&#8221; system of di=
stribution that mimicked &#8211; under the streets &#8211; the new parallel=
 circuits to be used within buildings. This brilliant new approach would </=
span><strong>cut copper costs to one-eighth the earlier estimates</strong><=
span>.</span></em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font=
-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">When asked why no one =
else had thought of this simple and elegant solution, Glasgow physicist Sir=
 William Thompson replied, &#8220;The only answer I can think of is that no=
 one else is Edison.&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Thompson was r=
ight, not because of Edison&#8217;s singular genius, but because Edison was=
 the only person in the world who </span><strong>had the entire system in h=
is head</strong><span>, who was thinking through distribution while having =
just designed the &#8220;parallel circuits to be used within buildings&#822=
1; and the high-resistance light bulb created to reduce the cost of copper =
in the system, and who was on the hook for delivering electric light at a c=
ost competitive with gas lighting.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(5=
4, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>=
With the system designed, Edison turned his team to production and implemen=
tation. His general, John Kruesi, manufactured and installed &#8220;(beneat=
h some of Manhattan&#8217;s busiest, filthiest thoroughfares) fourteen mile=
s of underground distribution cables and wires.&#8221; Charles Dean ran Edi=
son Machine Works, which manufactured generators by the East River. Francis=
 Upton produced a thousand light bulbs a day back at Menlo Park. </span><st=
rong>&#8220;These three enterprises,&#8221; Jones writes, &#8220;were all o=
rganized and financed by Edison or his closest associates.&#8221;&#160;</st=
rong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In August 1881, Edison bought a building in a gr=
imy neighborhood at 255-57 Pearl Street for $65,000, where &#8220;home-devi=
sed and home-made&#8221; devices &#8211; &#8220;Edison dynamos &#8211; powe=
red by coal-fired steam engines &#8211; produced an initial alternating cur=
rent electricity that was then gathered from the machine by &#8216;commutat=
ors&#8217; and brushes and turned into direct current.&#8221;&#160;</p><p s=
tyle=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin:=
 0 0 20px 0;">All the while, complications led to delays, as Edison&#8217;s=
 investors, the newspapers, and the public became increasingly frustrated. =
But on September 4, 1882, after &#8220;four years of hard work of the most =
original, difficult sort and almost $500,000,&#8221; John Lieb threw the ci=
rcuit breaker at Pearl Street and 400 incandescent light bulbs &#8220;glowe=
d softly to light.&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font=
-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The delays, costs, and=
 grumbling were forgotten in the flip of a switch. Edison was a hero, and a=
 rich one. In 1889, Edison consolidated his businesses into Edison General =
Electric Company, and in 1892, the company merged with Thomson-Houston Elec=
tric Company to form General Electric. The combined GE had an estimated mar=
ket cap of $35 million, roughly $1.2 billion in today&#8217;s dollars.&#160=
;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>That, however, was just the beginning of the <=
/span><strong>War of Currents</strong><span>. The next year, Westinghouse w=
on a victory for Nikola Tesla&#8217;s Alternating Current (AC) electricity =
over Edison&#8217;s DC when he lit up the 1893 Chicago World&#8217;s Fair. =
Ultimately, AC, which could travel longer distances, won out over DC.&#160;=
</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Historians remember Edison as having los=
t the war. From a technology perspective, that&#8217;s true. A true Vertica=
l Integrator, however, General Electric adopted the winning AC technology a=
nd plugged it into its </span><em>system</em><span>. The company leveraged =
its brand, size, resources, and diverse product line to invest heavily into=
 AC and used its large customer base to introduce new AC products to the ma=
rket.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In </span><em><a href=3D"http=
s://substack.com/redirect/48e863d4-441d-499b-8d1f-08d4ce4835a8?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color:=
 rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">My Life and Work</a><span>,<=
/span></em><span> Henry Ford said of Thomas Edison, &#8220;Edison is easily=
 the world&#8217;s greatest scientist. I am not sure that he is not also th=
e world&#8217;s worst business man. He knows almost nothing of business.&#8=
221; </span><em>&#160;</em></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>That may be true. Af=
ter merging with Thomson-Houston, Edison owned just 3-10% of the company hi=
s scientific brilliance brought to life. But the Vertical Integrator he cre=
ated won. </span><strong>Despite Tesla and Westinghouse winning the technol=
ogical war, General Electric remained the more valuable company throughout =
the Electric Age.&#160;</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fon=
t-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Study the past if you=
 want to define the future.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Today, we are =
entering a </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/65e857cb-a917-42=
2f-a28a-531cd126e085?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underli=
ne;">new Techno-Economic Paradigm</a><span>, like the one that Edison helpe=
d bring to life in the late 19th Century. General Electric was one of its b=
iggest winners, because at a time when vertical integration was needed to f=
igure out how to deliver new products to take advantage of new technologica=
l capabilities, it was a </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/ca=
bbe5f6-a560-4574-b74b-d48421812a44?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decor=
ation: underline;">textbook Vertical Integrator</a><span>:&#160;</span></p>=
<ol style=3D"margin-top: 0; padding: 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;=
"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;">Int=
egrate multiple cutting-edge-but-proven technologies.</p></li><li style=3D"=
margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(54, 5=
5, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; pa=
dding-left: 4px;">Develop significant in-house capabilities across their st=
ack.</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: bo=
rder-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;">Modularize commoditized compone=
nts while controlling overall system integration.</p></li><li style=3D"marg=
in: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 5=
5); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; paddin=
g-left: 4px;">Compete directly with incumbents.</p></li><li style=3D"margin=
: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55)=
; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-=
